lations were found for the tibial nerve conduction velocity (r = -0.24; 95% CI: -0.45, -0.01). Conclusion The amount and extension of T2-weighted hyperintense fascicular nerve lesions were greater in patients with painful diabetic neuropathy than in those with painless diabetic neuropathy. These results suggest that proximal fascicular damage is associated with the evolution of painful sensory symptoms in diabetic polyneuropathy. © RSNA, 2019 Online supplemental material is available for this article.
